import numpy as np

import datetime as dt
import seaborn as sns
import statsmodels.api as sm
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas_datareader.data as web

from stargazer.stargazer import Stargazer # Needs command install: pip install stargazer
from statsmodels.stats.outliers_influence import variance_inflation_factor

Initial Processing and Visualizations¶

Initial Processing¶

In [66]:
LaborStats = pd.read_csv('Warehousing_Conditions.csv')
TimeTrend = LaborStats['trend']

## Amazon_NFII_Estimate collinear with Inj_NFII_Rate_Monthly 
LaborStats = LaborStats.drop(columns = ['Inj_NFII_Rate_Monthly','trend'])

## Inflation-adjusting Amazon_Net_Income_Per_Worker and Hourly_Wage_Mean
cpi = web.DataReader("CPIAUCNS", "fred", 
                     dt.datetime(2011,1,1),
                     dt.datetime(2020,12,31))
cpi['year'] = cpi.index.year
cpi["month"] = cpi.index.month

cpi = cpi.groupby(['year','month'], as_index = False)[['CPIAUCNS']].mean()
cpi_DEC2020 = cpi.iloc[-1, 2]
LaborStats["CPIAUCNS"] = cpi["CPIAUCNS"]
LaborStats['Hourly_Wage_Mean'] = cpi.iloc[0,2]*LaborStats['Hourly_Wage_Mean']/LaborStats['CPIAUCNS']
LaborStats['Amazon_Net_Income_Per_Worker'] = cpi.iloc[0,2]*LaborStats['Amazon_Net_Income_Per_Worker']/LaborStats['CPIAUCNS']
LaborStats.drop(columns = ['CPIAUCNS'],inplace = True)

## QQ plots of variables
fig, axes = plt.subplots(3, 3, figsize=(20,20), constrained_layout = True)
fig.suptitle("Q-Q Plots of Baseline Model Variables", fontsize=16)
fig.delaxes(axes[2][1])
fig.delaxes(axes[2][2])

sm.qqplot(LaborStats['Amazon_Net_Income_Per_Worker'], line = 'r', ax = axes[0,0]);
sm.qqplot(LaborStats['Amazon_NFII_Estimate'], line = 'r', ax = axes[0,1]);

Visualizing Baseline Correlation¶

In [71]:
corr = LaborStats.drop(columns = ['year','month']).corr()
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 10))
colormap = sns.diverging_palette(220, 10, as_cmap = True)
dropvals = np.zeros_like(corr)
dropvals[np.triu_indices_from(dropvals)] = True
sns.heatmap(corr, cmap = colormap, linewidths = .5, annot = True, fmt = ".2f", mask = dropvals)
plt.title("Correlation Heatmap for Predictors in Amazon Net Income Per Worker")
plt.show()

Computing VIF for Multicollinearity¶

In [59]:
df_vif = LaborStats.drop(["Amazon_Net_Income_Per_Worker","month","year"], axis=1)

# VIF dataframe
vif_data = pd.DataFrame()
vif_data["feature"] = df_vif.columns
  
# calculating VIF for each feature
vif_data["VIF"] = [variance_inflation_factor(df_vif.values, i)
                          for i in range(len(df_vif.columns))]

Constructing Dummies and Interaction Variables¶

In [60]:
## Constructing interactions
LaborStats['Weekly_Hours_Hourly_Wage_Inter'] = LaborStats['Weekly_Hours_Mean'] * LaborStats['Hourly_Wage_Mean']
LaborStats['Weekly_Hours_Separation_Rate_Inter'] = LaborStats['Weekly_Hours_Mean'] * LaborStats['Separation_Rate']
LaborStats['Separation_Rate_strike_google_trend_Inter'] = LaborStats['Separation_Rate'] * LaborStats['strike_google_trend']
LaborStats['Amazon_NFII_Estimate_Days_Missed_Median_Inter'] = LaborStats['Amazon_NFII_Estimate'] * LaborStats['Inj_NFII_Days_Miss_Median_Monthly']

## Constructing dummies
### Add prefix so that stargaze works
YearDummy = pd.get_dummies(LaborStats['year'], drop_first = True).add_prefix("Year_")
MonthDummy = pd.get_dummies(LaborStats['month'], drop_first = True).add_prefix("Month_")

LaborStats = pd.concat([LaborStats,YearDummy,MonthDummy], axis = 1)
LaborStatsTrim = LaborStats.drop(columns = ['year','month'])

Constructing Models¶

Models with Constant¶

In [62]:
## Constructing models
Y = LaborStatsTrim["Amazon_Net_Income_Per_Worker"]
ModelList1 = [
    ## Model 1: Trimmed baseline -- Amazon_Net_Income_Per_Worker ~ Constant + Amazon_NFII_Estimate
    sm.OLS(Y,sm.add_constant(LaborStatsTrim['Amazon_NFII_Estimate'])).fit(),
    
    ## Model 2: Baseline; no yearly dummies or interactions
    sm.OLS(Y,sm.add_constant(LaborStatsTrim.iloc[:, 1:7])).fit(),
    
    ## Model 3: Baseline + yearly dummies; no interactions
    sm.OLS(Y,sm.add_constant(pd.concat([LaborStatsTrim.iloc[:, 1:7], LaborStatsTrim.iloc[:, 11:]], axis = 1))).fit(),
    
    ## Model 4: Baseline + interactions; no yearly dummies
    sm.OLS(Y,sm.add_constant(LaborStatsTrim.iloc[:, 1:11])).fit(),
    
    ## Model 5: Baseline + yearly dummies + interactions
    sm.OLS(Y,sm.add_constant(LaborStatsTrim.iloc[:, 1:])).fit()
] 

table = Stargazer(ModelList1)
table.title('Prototype Models')
table.covariate_order(['const','Amazon_NFII_Estimate','Inj_NFII_Days_Miss_Median_Monthly','Weekly_Hours_Mean','Hourly_Wage_Mean','Separation_Rate'])
table

ModelList2 = [
    ## Model 1: Trimmed baseline -- Amazon_Net_Income_Per_Worker ~ Amazon_NFII_Estimate
    sm.OLS(Y,LaborStatsTrim['Amazon_NFII_Estimate']).fit(),
    
    ## Model 2: Baseline; no yearly dummies or interactions
    sm.OLS(Y,LaborStatsTrim.iloc[:, 1:7]).fit(),
    
    ## Model 3: Baseline + yearly dummies; no interactions
    sm.OLS(Y,pd.concat([LaborStatsTrim.iloc[:, 1:7], LaborStatsTrim.iloc[:, 11:]], axis = 1)).fit(),
    
    ## Model 4: Baseline + interactions; no yearly dummies
    sm.OLS(Y,LaborStatsTrim.iloc[:, 1:11]).fit(),
    
    ## Model 5: Baseline + yearly dummies + interactions
    sm.OLS(Y,LaborStatsTrim.iloc[:, 1:]).fit()
]
